At the moment their eyes meet, Wress smiles slightly. Because he knows, ultimately, he's won. There is no realistic way the monarchy wins this battle. They are surrounded, and all odds are against them. He believes fully he is going to die very soon, but that his ideals will survive and thrive. So he's happy. Like an idiot.

At the moment their eyes meet, Zita's expression darkens, frowning slightly with a hopeless gaze in her eyes. It's not because she's realized this fact about the tactical impossibility of her victory. It's not even because of her identity being outed to the world, though that's certainly uncomfortable to her. No, it's because she feels *bad*. Because she internalizes she's murdering another stunted mentally ill child, someone she can't dehumanize as without the all important concept of Family since she's personally met his. So she feels regret for the thing she's currently still actively doing. She feels sad. Like an idiot.

messages.content:
"Your iteration..." PH stares confused for a moment. "Oh. Hm. Why were you even there?"

"Do you keep track of what happens in your project that little?!" Rene yells.

"I stay up to date on what's important."

"No you don't."

"I do. I can't be bothered to track some asinine technicality about unimportant non-participant parties. Do you expect me to remember Richard Ogden?" PH gestures to the air to indicate the absurdity of such a thing. "I do, but only because I was directly involved."

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
"You've only been involved in one meaningful thing in your entire miserable life." Rene closes the distance between the two of them. "And you spent years not remaining up to date. And here you are doing it again."

PH is uncomfortable with this amount of closeness, and gets out of his seat. "I don't..."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
"I am not interested in excuses."

"Okay, then what *are* you interested in?" PH snaps. "Why are you even here? Are you that clingy to someone you claim disinterest in, that you show up to inform me of every trifling detail?"

Rene blinks. "Um. I. I mean. I thought it was important you know, since you nominally have some responsibility. And I demand you send me back."

"Back? You don't even know that anything happened there. In fact, you have no idea *when* it happened. Maybe you're confusing some signal from way in the distant future."

"We both know that is not how it works." Rene glares. "I am dead, or close to it. Erica will likely be mildly upset by this, which is unacceptable."

"...I will never understand what went wrong with you."

"No, you wouldn't." She smiles. "I'm not asking. This is an order. We both know I'm capable of outmatching you in a physical altercation."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
"Well, I can't. It doesn't work that way." PH scowls. "Do you think I'm an idiot? That I wouldn't have tried testing that? If you're out of the picture in Arctica, that's your own problem to reap the consequences of."

Rene stares. She does a lot of staring. She grabs PH by the neck. "Is that so? You sure you want to stick to that?"

"Ngh." He sweats. "...Yes. It's the truth, and I'm sure you have the sense to understand that." He isn't sure of this in the slightest.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
"..." Rene lets him go. "Very well."

"Are you going to actually do what I asked?" PH mutters, recovering quickly from a brush with murderous intent.

"Perhaps. I also want The Antarctica Project to... properly conclude." Rene turns to exit.

"Ominous. But I'm already aware you hope Big Man breaks all my bones or somesuch."

"Ha ha." Rene chuckles. It's an artificial sounding laugh.

It will right the wrongs of the world, finally set in motion a more proper order of things. No more secrets. No more hiding. No more fear. It will be the greatest moment, she thinks, of her entire excuse for a life.

Because it will be the worst moment of his.

messages.content:
During a low point for both of us, in a period that is by now over a decade in the past, my longtime friend Zaquera Culbasko came to me with a… shocking proposition.

I had always seen Zaquera as, while not reasonable, someone who rarely did things which were highly risky without a chance to tangibly benefit him. So upon hearing about what would become known as “The Antarctica Project” (not in any sense the first thing to confusingly use a name very similar to this set of words), and having my involvement requested, I was quite surprised. But I was weak. I had recently undergone some very personally taxing emotional drama related to family. I was fearful of death more than ever, tantalized by an opportunity to do research again. I accepted. And I… rekindled my relationship with him.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I don’t know why. I’ve spent my entire life since asking myself that question. I’d spent my entire life prior trying to achieve meaning and impact the world via technology. Maybe I just thought I should try something different. In my inane, deluded emotions, it might have seemed like a miracle that I was even still capable of that type of ‘creation’ at all. A sign of what I should do with my life. It was irrational. But I only became paralyzed by fear too late. Some people aren’t cut out to be parents. Detlef Praxis wanders through the outskirts of the capital province, having evacuated. This is long before anything that takes place after a timeskip, obviously. A guard escorts him. Just a normal one, not guard with a capital G.

“I just… I mean, I get why people like that Wress guy might’ve been upset. It just seems pretty foolish to throw out everything rather than just fix the system we already have. You know? I know Catarina and Zita are both reasonable women. Surely they could’ve simply, uh, talked it out, somehow.”

The guard’s eyes widen. She gasps.

“A waste of time.” Solnit shakes his head. “It isn’t as though I’ve cut contact with Dextrum. He knows everything I could tell him.”

“And everything I’m willing to disclose.” Isador Dechai smirks slyly, resting a leg on the table in the center of this currently-functioning-as-a-waiting-room. “I imagine it’s more of a matter of finally getting some in-person testimony now that there’s something closer to a functional government around to keep records.” He sighs.

“This selection of people is stupid.” Gratia mutters. She’s alive, it turns out. Wow. No way. “I got nothin’ to say to the feds.”

“You acquiesced to come here, did you not?” Solnit questions, gesturing dramatically within his robe, a newer and more ostentatious outfit than his previous nonsense.

“I thought I could pilfer shit from the venue. You know. Gratia at the Function, what will she do? Hah.”

“True.” Isador.

Solnit doesn’t understand this. “Are you not busy sucking up to Voreverl, or something?”

“Haha, that’s…!” Gratia looks down. “M…maybe eventually. I mean, once I can… when I get over…”
She goes silent.

“Incomprehensible.” Solnit scoffs. “And you? Are you not worried our new king-who-isn’t-calling-himself-that will apprehend you as the criminal you are?”

“Nah, Dexie and I go way back.” Isador mutters.

“Dexie?! I highly doubt that.”

“Well, we ain’t exactly friends. Still haven’t forgiven him for… well, it was my fault as much. Should’ve been able to protect him.”

“Protect… Virtos?”

“No.” Isador doesn’t elaborate, but he’s obviously thinking about his dead brother or whatever. “And you? I guess going AWOL to run a cult hasn’t dampened your need to be his lapdog.”

“It is NOT a cult - merely a society based on principled logical beliefs, and the evident probability of Eulogia’s return - and also I hate him, and I’m here to keep up appearances.”

“Appearances of what?” Isador questions.

“You wouldn’t get it.” Solnit shakes his head.

“Yeah.” Isador doesn’t say anything else.
